EON, Continental, Deutsche Telekom, QSC: German Equity Preview

-- B y   B r i a n   P a r k i n   a n d   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-08-08T06:43:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-07/e-on-continental-deutsche-telekom-german-equities-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in  Germany . Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close.  DAX Index (DAX)  futures expiring in September dropped 2.1 percent
to 6,123.50 as of 8:18 a.m. in Frankfurt. The benchmark DAX
Index slid 178.60 points, or 2.8 percent, to 6236.16 on Aug. 5.  Bayer AG (BAYN)  : The Leverkusen-based chemical maker may
move some production away from Germany to cut energy costs that
may rise as the country pursues a quicker phase-out from nuclear
power, Chief Executive Officer Marijn Dekkers was cited as
saying in an interview in WirtschaftsWoche weekly. The shares
fell 3.8 percent to 48.72 euros.  Continental AG (CON)  :  Europe ’s second-largest car-parts
maker expects to continue expanding its workforce from the
current 160,000 employees as sales grow in all five of its
market segments, Automotive News Europe cited Chief Executive
Officer Elmar Degenhart as saying. The stock fell 2.8 percent to
57.90 euros.  Deutsche Telekom AG (DTE)  : The Bonn-based company may
seek talks with competitors such as Vodafone Group Plc and
Telefonica SA over potentially sharing the costs of building a
high-speed VDSL Internet network in Germany, Focus magazine
reported, citing an interview with management-board member Niek Jan van Damme. The stock fell 1.7 percent to 9.97 euros.  EON AG (EOAN GY): Germany’s largest utility may cut as many
as 10,000 jobs globally as it seeks savings in the wake of an
accelerated phase-out of nuclear power at home,  Sueddeutsche
Zeitung  reported, without saying where it got the information.  Separately, the stock was downgraded to “hold” from
“buy” at Societe Generale SA. The shares fell 3 percent to
17.27 euros.  Hannover Re  (HNR1 GY): The insurer said second-quarter net
income was 166.2 million euros ($239 million), exceeding an
average analyst estimate of 151 million euros. The shares
declined 0.5 percent to 32.27 euros.  QSC AG (QSC GY): The broadband network operator reiterated
its forecast for the full year for a cash flow of 35 million
euros to 45 million euros and said it plans to distribute a
dividend. Net income fell to 3.9 million euros in the second
quarter from 4.3 million euros in the same quarter one year
earlier. The shares were unchanged at 2.25 euros.  Rhoen-Klinikum AG (RHK)  : The operator of emergency
health-care facilities was raised to “overweight” from
“equal-weight” at Morgan Stanley. The shares slumped 2.6
percent to 16.11 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
